# Summary
Introduced: the commit added an unpinned runtime dependency execution path in both CI and the release workflow. The release workflow instance is security significant because it precedes artifact creation and runs in a job with repository write permission.
The new Go vulnerability check is executed as `go run golang.org/x/vuln/cmd/govulncheck@latest ./...` in the release workflow. Because `@latest` is resolved at workflow runtime rather than being pinned in the repository, a compromised or malicious future `golang.org/x/vuln` release would execute arbitrary code on the GitHub Actions runner. In the release job, this occurs with `contents: write` permission and before the application is built, packaged, hashed, and uploaded. That malicious code could modify source files, alter the built executable, replace release artifacts, or abuse persisted checkout credentials/release permissions. This is a supply-chain release-integrity issue introduced by the commit. Pinning govulncheck to a reviewed version, tracking it through a tools module/lockfile, and reducing permissions until the publish step would reduce the risk.

# Validation
## Rubric
- [x] Confirm the commit introduced `go run golang.org/x/vuln/cmd/govulncheck@latest ./...` in release/CI workflows.
- [x] Confirm the release workflow has elevated repository permission (`contents: write`) when this step runs.
- [x] Confirm the unpinned tool execution occurs before build, package, checksum, and release upload steps.
- [x] Confirm govulncheck is not pinned or tracked through `go.mod`, `go.sum`, or another tools lockfile in the repository.
- [x] Dynamically demonstrate that the exact `go run ...@latest` command executes code resolved at runtime and can write/tamper within the workspace.
## Report
Validated the finding as a workflow supply-chain/release-integrity issue. The commit changed only `.github/workflows/ci.yml` and `.github/workflows/release.yml`; `git show` confirmed the new govulncheck steps were introduced in this commit. In `.github/workflows/release.yml`, repository write permission is granted at lines 9-10 (`permissions: contents: write`). The release job checks out the repository at lines 18-19, then runs the unpinned command at lines 50-52: `go run golang.org/x/vuln/cmd/govulncheck@latest ./...`. The build and packaging steps occur only afterward at lines 54-83, including artifact zip creation, checksum creation, and upload through `softprops/action-gh-release@v2`. CI has the same unpinned execution at `.github/workflows/ci.yml:73-75`. A targeted grep found no pinned govulncheck/tooling reference in `.github` or `src/go.mod`/`src/go.sum`, only the two `@latest` invocations. To dynamically validate the execution primitive without network access, I created a local Go module proxy containing a fake future `golang.org/x/vuln` version `v0.0.999` with `cmd/govulncheck` code that writes marker files. Running the same workflow command from `src` with `GOPROXY` pointed at that proxy executed the malicious code and created markers in the source tree and pre-build `dist` area. Captured output: `MALICIOUS GOVULNCHECK POC EXECUTED`, followed by marker contents showing `cwd=/workspace/ClipForVRChat/src` and `args=[.../govulncheck ./...]`. This demonstrates that whatever code resolves as `@latest` at workflow runtime executes before the release artifact build/package/upload steps, so a malicious or compromised future upstream govulncheck release could tamper with release inputs/artifacts. Crash/valgrind/debugger validation is not applicable to this workflow-configuration supply-chain issue; additionally `gdb` and `valgrind` were not present in the container.

