# Attack-path analysis
Final: high | Decider: model_decided | Matrix severity: high | Policy adjusted: high
## Rationale
Severity is kept at high, not critical. The issue is real and in scope: `.github/workflows/release.yml` grants `contents: write` and executes `go run golang.org/x/vuln/cmd/govulncheck@latest ./...` before build, packaging, checksum creation, and release upload. The validation evidence shows the exact primitive can execute attacker-controlled module code and write into the workspace. Impact is high because official release artifacts can be compromised. Likelihood is low because exploitation depends on compromise or malicious control of the upstream golang.org/x/vuln module and a subsequent release run; no direct signing-key compromise or public unauthenticated application RCE is evidenced. The probability-impact combination supports high release-integrity risk but not critical.
## Likelihood
high - The vulnerable command is definitely reachable during release runs, and a validation PoC demonstrated arbitrary code execution from a runtime-resolved module. However, a real attacker must first compromise or maliciously publish the upstream govulncheck module selected by `@latest`, making practical exploitation relatively uncommon and higher complexity. | Remote network vector
## Impact
high - Successful exploitation can affect official release integrity: malicious code running before build and package can alter the executable, zip, or checksum that are uploaded to GitHub Releases. This can propagate to end users who trust the official release channel.
## Assumptions
- The release workflow is used to publish official end-user Windows release artifacts.
- A future malicious or compromised golang.org/x/vuln module version would be selected by @latest during a release run.
- GitHub Actions default checkout credential behavior is in effect unless overridden; the workflow does not set persist-credentials: false.
- No external GitHub repository settings, environment protection rules, or branch/tag protections were inspected because analysis is limited to repository artifacts.
- Attacker controls or compromises a future golang.org/x/vuln/cmd/govulncheck module version resolved by @latest
- A release workflow run occurs through tag push or workflow_dispatch
- The unpinned govulncheck step runs before build, packaging, checksum, and release upload
## Path
Attacker controls govulncheck release -> release job runs `go run ...@latest` -> code executes in workspace with contents:write job -> source/artifact tampering -> build/package/checksum -> GitHub Release -> users
## Path evidence
- `.github/workflows/release.yml:9-10` - The release workflow grants repository `contents: write` permission to the job.
- `.github/workflows/release.yml:18-19` - The repository is checked out before the unpinned tool runs, creating a workspace that malicious tool code could modify.
- `.github/workflows/release.yml:50-52` - The workflow executes govulncheck via `go run ...@latest`, causing runtime resolution and execution of unpinned third-party Go code.
- `.github/workflows/release.yml:57-60` - The application build occurs after the unpinned govulncheck execution.
- `.github/workflows/release.yml:62-83` - Packaging, checksum creation, and release upload occur after the unpinned code has had an opportunity to tamper with the workspace.
- `.github/workflows/ci.yml:73-75` - The same unpinned govulncheck execution also exists in CI, although CI has only contents:read and is less impactful than release.
## Narrative
The finding is a real release-pipeline supply-chain issue. The release job grants `contents: write`, checks out the repository, then executes `go run golang.org/x/vuln/cmd/govulncheck@latest ./...`. That command downloads and executes code selected at workflow runtime rather than code pinned in this repository. The application build, zip packaging, SHA256 generation, and GitHub Release upload all occur afterward, so malicious code in a future compromised govulncheck release could modify sources or artifacts before they become official releases. The issue is in scope because release integrity is part of the project threat model. Severity remains high due to potential compromise of official artifacts, but likelihood is low because exploitation requires compromise or malicious publication of an upstream Go module version and a subsequent release run.
## Controls
- CI workflow uses `contents: read`, reducing impact for the CI instance of the issue.
- Release workflow is limited to tag pushes and manual `workflow_dispatch`, so exploitation requires a release run.
- Go module checksum validation can detect content substitution for known versions but does not prevent malicious code in a newly published latest version.
- Generated SHA256 checksum is not an independent control because it is produced after the potentially compromised build/package step.
- No repository artifact shows govulncheck pinned in go.mod, go.sum, or a tools lockfile.
## Blindspots
- Static repository analysis cannot verify GitHub branch/tag protection, required reviewers, environment protection, or organization Actions policies.
- Static analysis cannot confirm actual GitHub Actions runtime token exposure beyond workflow permissions and standard action behavior.
- No cloud or GitHub APIs were called, so current release usage, installed secrets, and repository settings were not inspected.
- The workflow does not show a detached release signature step in the inspected file, so conclusions are limited to executable zip and checksum integrity.
